english:
  title: A Farewell Sequence for Monk Rim's Journey to Jirisan
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The sky towers high, the air runs clear. Autumn grain fills the countryside fields—a most auspicious season for the Venerable One's departure.

    The Venerable One, having transcended the mundane world, has devoted himself to the dharma of the Great Sage. He spurns the dust and tumult of this realm, and now raises his staff to journey southward, seeking to traverse the full span of what mortal eyes can behold. Who would not look up in admiration at such lofty footprints?

    When I, a man grown old in learning, heard of this, my heart soared like a small dove yearning for the great Peng bird, celebrating in the grandeur of such southern ambition. I asked where he was bound, and learned he would enter Jirisan—the Mountain of Flowing Heads.

    Jirisan's waters spring from distant sources. The great white peaks stand in the lands of northern barbarians. Their ramifications extend and spread, branching eastward as Iron Ridge and Paulownia Ridge, converging as Spirit Pagoda Mountain, Five Terrace Peak, and Great White Mountain. Turning westward again, they become Bamboo Ridge and Bird Ridge. Spreading southward, they ultimately bend down to the Southern Sea itself—this is Jirisan. Where its great form seems ready to shatter, strange and magnificent, pure and luminous qi gathers and billows forth, confined yet unspilling. Thus the mountain's peaks rise sharp and elegant, its grasses and trees flourish luxuriantly. Immortals and monks cultivate their nature there. Many who wish to behold such wonders find it beyond their reach.

    Once, traveling southward through the lands of Hamyang and Jinju, I glimpsed a mountain of great height, half-veiled in clouds—the very Heaven King Peak of this range. I inquired of the post officials; the distance, they said, was near. They told me that Choi Go-un's great calligraphy remained vividly carved upon the rock face. My heart leapt with joy, yet my horse pressed onward with urgency, and I had no leisure to visit. To this day it grieves me.

    Go-un was the founder of our nation's literary way. Even servants know his name and revere it—how much more so the Venerable One! When the Venerable One returns, may he hold Go-un's heart as his heart, learn Go-un's learning, and walk Go-un's paths. Though robes and form differ, there is something deeper that remains the same. Zhuge Liang was the sage-counselor of kings, and Tao Yuanming was a recluse scholar, yet each moved through life guided by noble spirit. How much more so, then, when one treads the very ground where Go-un walked, witnesses the scenes he witnessed? The admiration runs far deeper.

    I am one who yearns for Jirisan. I am one who reveres Go-un. I am one who admires the Venerable One's journey yet cannot follow. On his departure, I have no grand words to offer, only what dwells within my heart—which I now inscribe and send in farewell.
  footnotes:
    - 'Monk Rim (林上人): A Buddhist monk undertaking a pilgrimage through Korea''s sacred landscape.'
    - 'Jirisan (지리산): Known in Chinese as Togyesan (두류산), one of the three sacred Buddhist mountains of Korea, located on the border of three provinces.'
    - 'Go-un (최고운, Choi Go-un): The poet-philosopher Choi Chi-won (857-?), Korea''s first great poet-statesman and Buddhist scholar, often regarded as the founder of Korean literary tradition.'
    - 'The great Peng bird: A reference to Zhuangzi''s mythical bird that embodies transcendence and spiritual aspiration.'
    - 'Zhuge Liang and Tao Yuanming: Referenced as exemplars of those who pursued higher ideals despite their different roles—one as a political counselor, one as a recluse.'
    - The author, Seong Hyeon (성현, 1439-1504), was a prominent Joseon scholar and official, famous for compiling the Dongunseon (Eastern Texts), a major anthology of Korean classical literature.
